ck docs/api/matching.md\n7. Check if there are .feature files\n\nAlso I noticed:
\n- `tests/bdd/step-definitions/matching_mutual_like_creates_match.steps.js` lin
e 39: "both users should receive a match notification via Socket.io" just checks
`expect(this.result.isMatch).toBe(true)` - this doesn\'t actually test Socket.io
emission at all. The socket emission happens in the controller, not the service,
so the BDD step is testing the wrong layer.\n- The BDD step definitions referenc
e `../matching_card_recommendations.feature` but I need to check if these files 
exist.\n- `matching-common.js` imports from `../../../apps/api/dist/modules/matc
hing/matching.service` - this means the BDD tests require the API to be built fi
rst. That\'s a dependency issue but not necessarily blocking.\n- In `matching.se
rvice.ts`, the `queryCandidates` method doesn\'t filter by `age_range_min` and `
age_range_max` of the target user. The PRD says "目标用户资料完整" but doesn\'t 
specifically mention age range filtering. Let me re-read... The PRD mentions "目
标用户性别符合当前用户的 preferred_gender" and "当前用户性别符合目标用户的 prefe
rred_gender" but doesn\'t mention age range. So this might be okay.\n- But wait,
`queryCandidates` also doesn\'t filter by the current user\'s `age_range_min` an
d `age_range_max`. The PRD doesn\'t explicitly require this, so it\'s not a bloc
king issue.\n- The `maxDistance` for `city` mode is 50km, same as nearby. The PR
D says city mode should be "同城市，根据用户当前位置行政边界" but this is not im
plemented. This is a Major issue.\n- Actually, looking at the PRD more carefully
: "mode 参数：nearby（默认 50km）、city（同城市，根据用户当前位置行政边界）、nat
ionwide（全国）". The implementation treats city as 50km. This is a functional d
eviation but the PRD itself acknowledges this is complex (行政边界). I\'ll mark 
it as Major.\n- The `matching.gateway.ts` has `handleConnection` which joins the
client to `user:${payload.sub}` room. Then `emitMatchCreated` emits to `user:${u
serAId}` and `user:${userBId}`. This is correct for Socket.io.\n- BUT: I don\'t 
see any client-side socket connection setup in the mobile code! The `HomePage` o
r `MatchingBloc` should connect to the socket and listen for `match:created`. Th
e docs/modules/matching.md says "在 HomePage 的 initState 中建立 Socket 连接（或
通过全局 BLoC）" and "监听 match:created 事件，接收到后向 MatchingBloc dispatch 
ExternalMatchReceived(matchSummary)". But the actual `HomePage` code doesn\'t ha
ve any socket setup. This is Blocking!\n- Also, `MatchingBloc._onExternalMatchRe
ceived` just emits `MatchingMatchCreated` but doesn\'t preserve the current card
s. After dismissing the modal (which emits `MatchingLoadEmpty`), the user loses 
their card stack.\n- `_onMatchModalDismissed` always emits `MatchingLoadEmpty(mo
de: \'nearby\')` - it doesn\'t check if there are remaining cards or preserve th
e mode. This is Blocking because if you match and dismiss the modal, you lose yo
ur cards.\n- Wait, looking at `_onSwipeActionSubmitted`: after emitting `Matchin
gMatchCreated`, it emits `MatchingLoadSuccess(cards: remainingCards, mode: curre
ntState.mode)` or `MatchingLoadEmpty`. So after a match, the state becomes `Matc
hingLoadSuccess` with remaining cards. Then when the user dismisses the modal, `
_onMatchModalDismissed` overwrites it with `MatchingLoadEmpty(mode: \'nearby\')`
. So yes, remaining cards are lost. Blocking.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider. The
dialog is shown via `BlocConsumer` listener. When `MatchingMatchCreated` is emit
ted, `_showMatchDialog` is called. The dialog is a modal that blocks interaction
. The user then presses "继续滑动" which calls `Navigator.of(context).pop()` and
then dispatches `MatchModalDismissed`. At that point, the state is whatever was 
emitted last. Looking at `_onSwipeActionSubmitted`:\n\n```dart\nif (response.dat
a.isMatch == true) {\n  emit(MatchingMatchCreated({...}));\n}\n\nif (remainingCa
rds.isEmpty) {\n  emit(MatchingLoadEmpty(mode: currentState.mode));\n} else {\n 
emit(MatchingLoadSuccess(cards: remainingCards, mode: currentState.mode));\n}\n`
``\n\nSo `MatchingMatchCreated` is immediately followed by `MatchingLoadSuccess`
or `MatchingLoadEmpty`. The listener gets both states. `_showMatchDialog` is cal
led when `MatchingMatchCreated` is emitted. But then immediately after, the stat
e becomes `MatchingLoadSuccess` or `MatchingLoadEmpty`. The dialog is still show
n (it\'s a modal). When the user dismisses it and dispatches `MatchModalDismisse
d`, the handler emits `MatchingLoadEmpty(mode: \'nearby\')` regardless of what t
he current state is. \n\nIf the cards were not empty before the match, after dis
missal they become empty. That\'s definitely a bug. And even if cards were empty
, the mode is hardcoded to \'nearby\'. If the user was in \'nationwide\' mode, i
t switches back to \'nearby\'. Blocking.\n\nLet me also check if there are mobil
e unit tests for the matching bloc. Looking at the file list, I don\'t see any `
matching_bloc_test.dart` or similar. The only test file is `dev_tools_widget_tes
t.dart`. This means:\n- No widget tests for matching components\n- No unit tests
for MatchingBloc\n- No unit tests for MatchListCubit\nThis is a Major issue for 
test coverage.\n\nAlso, the `SwipeCardStack` organism in design-system is basica
lly a copy of `_CardStackArea` in `home_page.dart`. The `HomePage` doesn\'t use 
`SwipeCardStack` - it uses its own private `_CardStackArea`. So the design syste
m component `SwipeCardStack` is not actually used. That\'s a Major issue for des
ign system consistency.\n\nAlso, looking at `home_page.dart` line 224: `_showMat
chDialog` gets `match[\'matched_user\']?[\'nickname\']` but `MatchingBloc._onSwi
peActionSubmitted` only puts `{\'user_id\': event.targetId}` in matched_user. So
